<div class="advancedSearchHelpWrapper">
  <details class="expandableSection">
    <summary>
      <span class="summaryContainer">
        <span class="summaryChevron" aria-label="expand/collapse icon"></span>
        Need help with advanced search?
      </span>
    </summary>
    <section class="searchHelpSection">
      <ul class="advancedSearchCheatSheet">
        <li>
          <code>|</code>
          signifies an OR operation
        </li>
        <li>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <code>-</code>
              negates a single word
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
          <code>&quot;</code>
          wraps a word or phrase you want to match exactly
        </li>
        <li>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <code>*</code>
              at the end of a term signifies a prefix query
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
          <code>( )</code>
          allow you to group terms
        </li>
        <li>
          <code>~N</code>
          after a <strong>word</strong> relaxes spelling rules (fuzziness)
        </li>
        phrase
        <li>
          <code>~N</code>
          after a <strong>phrase</strong> signifies slop amount (<a
            href="#Slop_84"
            >see below for more details</a
          >)
        </li>
      </ul>
      <h2><a id="AND_OR_8"></a>AND, OR</h2>
      <p>
        By default, the search returns pages that contain all words in your
        query. If you want to search for pages that contain the words
        “configure”, or “install”, or “manage”, enter:
      </p>
      <pre><code>configure | install | manage</code></pre>
      <h2><a id="Excluding_NOT_18"></a>Excluding (NOT)</h2>
      <p>
        If you want pages that contain the word “configure” and “manage” but not
        “install”, enter:
      </p>
      <pre><code>configure -install manage</code></pre>
      <p>
        The order of these words in your search query does not matter.
      </p>
      <h2><a id="Exact_match_29"></a>Exact match</h2>
      <p>
        If you want an exact phrase to match, surround it with double quotes:
      </p>
      <pre><code>&quot;manage user accounts&quot;</code></pre>
      <h2><a id="Grouping_37"></a>Grouping</h2>
      <p>
        If you want to exclude multiple terms, you can group them with
        parentheses. For example:
      </p>
      <pre><code>configure -(install manage)</code></pre>
      <p>
        You can also combine double quotes with other methods. For example to
        find the phrase “manage user accounts” and the words “policy” or “group”
        but not “PolicyCenter”, enter:
      </p>
      <pre><code>&quot;manage users&quot; (policy | group) -PolicyCenter</code></pre>
      <p>
        A phrase in double quotes takes precedence in highlighting.
      </p>
      <p>
        Note that our search uses stemming, which means that if you search for
        “configure” you will also see results for “configuring” and
        “configuration”. If you want to match a word exactly, use double quotes.
      </p>
      <h2><a id="Prefix_60"></a>Prefix</h2>
      <p>
        If you want to find words that have a common beginning, like BigDecimal
        and BigInt, you can use a prefix query with an asterisk:
      </p>
      <pre><code>big*</code></pre>
      <p>
        If you are having trouble finding pages using a prefix query, try lower
        case in your query.
      </p>
      <p>
        We do not support suffix search for now (<code>*decimal</code>), but you
        can get more results using fuzziness.
      </p>
      <h2><a id="Fuzziness_75"></a>Fuzziness</h2>
      <p>
        You can relax the spelling rules a little if you add a ~ and a number
        after a word. For example, if you’re not sure if you want “center” or
        “centre”, try:
      </p>
      <pre><code>centre~1</code></pre>
      <h2><a id="Slop_84"></a>Slop</h2>
      <p>
        If you want to match phrases like “Model Info screen”, “Model Details
        screen”, and the like, you can surround a simple phrase with quotes and
        follow it by a ~ and a number.
      </p>
      <pre><code>&quot;model screen&quot;~1</code></pre>
      <p>
        This number specifies the amount of “slop” in the phrase. The query
        above means you’re looking for a phrase that contains the words “model”
        and “screen”, but one word can be inserted into the phrase between the
        first and the last word.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you specify something like:
      </p>
      <pre><code>&quot;gosu zones types&quot;~5</code></pre>
      <p>
        That means you want the words “gosu”, “zones”, and “types”, but you
        allow up to 5 words to be inserted anywhere in the phrase, but between
        the first and the last word. With the phrase above, you can match
        &quot;<strong>Gosu</strong> holiday methods that use
        <strong>zones</strong> and <strong>types</strong>&quot;.
      </p>
      <p>
        Have fun searching! 🙂
      </p>
    </section>
  </details>
